{{Main article|Dyslexia|Theories of dyslexia}} The double-deficit [[theory]] of [[dyslexia]]<ref>{{Cite journal |author1=Wolf, M. |author2= Bowers, P. |last-author-amp=yes |title=The "Double-Deficit Hypothesis" for the developmental dyslexias |publisher=Journal of Educational Psychology, 91, 1-24. |year=1999 |postscript=<!-- Bot inserted parameter. Either remove it; or change its value to "." for the cite to end in a ".", as necessary. -->{{inconsistent citations}}}}</ref><ref>Bowers PG. Wolf M. (1993). Theoretical links among naming speed, precise timing mechanisms and orthographic skill in dyslexia. Reading and Writing, 5:69-85. {{DOI|10.1007/BF01026919}}</ref> proposes that a [[Cognitive deficit|deficit]] in two essential skills gives rise to the lowest level of reading performances, constituting the most severe form of [[dyslexia]].
==Reading ability== The ability to read is believed to depend on two skills:
*'''[[Phonological awareness|Phonological processing]]''' skills make up the ability to identify and manipulate sounds in speech. *'''[[Rapid automatized naming]]''' compose the ability to translate visual information whether of letters, objects or pictures into a phonological code.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Denckla | first1 = MB | last2 = Rudel | first2 = R | title = Rapid "automatized" naming of pictured objects, colors, letters and numbers by normal children. | journal = Cortex | volume = 10 | issue = 2 | pages = 186–202 | year = 1974 | pmid = 4844470 | doi=10.1016/s0010-9452(74)80009-2}}</ref>
